    Personal portfolio

    I'll create a modern, responsive personal portfolio website for you using Next.js and Tailwind CSS. This portfolio will include sections for your introduction, about, projects, and contact information.

    Version 1

    This portfolio website includes:

    1. Header with navigation links and a contact button
    2. Hero Section with your profile picture, name, and social links
    3. About Section with your bio and skills
    4. Projects Section showcasing your work with images and descriptions
    5. Contact Section with a form and contact information
    6. Footer with copyright information and additional links

    How to Customize

    1. Replace the placeholder images with your own photos
    2. Update the personal information (name, email, social links)
    3. Add your actual projects with descriptions and screenshots
    4. Customize the skills list to match your expertise
    5. Update the contact information with your actual details

    The design is fully responsive and works well on mobile, tablet, and desktop devices. It uses a clean, modern aesthetic with Tailwind CSS for styling and shadcn/ui components for the UI elements.

    You can deploy this portfolio to Vercel by clicking the "Deploy" button in the top right corner of the UI.

    Version 3
    Edited
    Edited

    I've fixed the error by:

    1. Replacing the ThemeToggle component with a simpler implementation that:

      • Uses React's built-in useState and useEffect hooks
      • Directly manipulates the dark class on the HTML element
      • Stores the theme preference in localStorage
      • Provides the same visual toggle between sun and moon icons

    2. Simplifying the layout.tsx file by:

      • Removing the ThemeProvider component which was causing the error
      • Keeping the suppressHydrationWarning attribute to prevent hydration mismatch warnings

    This implementation provides the same dark/light mode functionality but without relying on the next-themes library, which was causing the error. The toggle will now work correctly, adding or removing the dark class from the HTML element, which will trigger the dark mode styles defined in your globals.css file.

    The theme will also persist between page refreshes thanks to localStorage, and it will initially respect the user's system preference if they haven't explicitly set a theme.
